Safety systems include:

    Pressure relief valves on all pressure vessels;
    Compressor safety cutouts and control panels to shut down the compressor operation if safe operating conditions are exceeded;
    Liquid level float switches;
    High level vessel alarms;
    Ventilation system for continuous and emergency ventilation;
    Emergency Control Station with emergency ventilation fan switch and emergency shutdown switch;
    Ammonia detection and alarm system for response to elevated levels of ammonia vapor.  Detection will trigger the emergency ventilation system, emergency shutdown, and audible/visual alarms at preset levels;
    Spring-loaded, self-closing oil drain valves;
    Manual stop valves;
    Manual and solenoid-controlled A?King ValveA? to stop liquid refrigerant flow discharge from the high-pressure receiver;
    Physical barriers to protect equipment/piping from collisions (e.g. bollards);
    Fire extinguishers; and
    Emergency showers and eyewash stations

System conditions are monitored daily by a trained and qualified maintenance staff, which also performs minor maintenance.  Major maintenance activities are contracted to a qualified refrigeration contractor (see Mechanical Integrity program for more information).  The ammonia refrigeration systems are monitored 24 hours per day and are also managed and controlled by the system PLC, safety switches, level switches, alarms, and compressor microprocessors.  All personnel are trained in the proper emergency response procedures.  The facility maintains an Emergency Action Plan for response to ammonia releases.  The Plan includes notification and evacuation protocols.

